{{Infobox award | name = Lilienthal Gliding Medal | image = | imagesize = 200px | caption = Averse of the Lilienthal Medal | description = Remarkable performance in [[gliding]], or eminent services to the sport of gliding over a long period of time | presenter = [[Fédération Aéronautique Internationale]] (FAI) | country = International | reward = | year = 1938 | year2 = 2017 | website = [http://www.fai.org/awards/fai-awards-for-individual-disciplines Official site] }} [[Image:Lilienthal medal-obverse.jpg|thumb|200px|Obverse of the Lilienthal Medal]] [[Image:Lilienthal medal-revers.jpg|thumb|200px|Reverse of the Lilienthal Medal awarded to [[Tadeusz Góra]]]] '''Lilienthal Gliding Medal''' – the highest soaring award in the world, established by [[Fédération Aéronautique Internationale]] (FAI) in 1938 in honor of [[Otto Lilienthal]], a [[Germany|German]] pioneer of human [[aviation]]. It aims "to reward a particularly remarkable performance in [[gliding]], or eminent services to the sport of gliding over a long period of time". The award is made at the annual FAI General Conference.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ssa.org/myhome.asp?mbr=7262842059&show=blog&id=812#Lilienthal|title= SSA Awards and SSA Recognized Awards - International Awards|publisher= Soaring Society of America |accessdate= 2011-02-22}}</ref> Medal was designed by [[Austria]]n artist Josef Humplik.
The first winner of the Lilienthal Gliding Medal in the world was [[Tadeusz Góra]] for his record-breaking 577.8-kilometer flight on May 18, 1938, glider PWS-101 from [[Bezmiechowa Górna|Bezmiechowa]] to [[Šalčininkai|Soleczniki]] (near [[Vilnius]]).
The Medal is awarded by a vote of the Delegates to the [[FAI Gliding Commission|International Gliding Commission]] at the annual Plenary in March. In 2012 it was decided to end the practice of awarding the Medal for accomplishments of the previous calendar year, and to associate the Medal with the year in which the recipient is determined. Consequently, the year 2013 does not appear in the table below.
